hropshire, England":"Ellesmere, Shropshire, England","Ellesmere, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ellesmere, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ellesmere Port, Cheshire, England":"Netherpool, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"1310–":"1310–Deceased","1310–Female":"1310–Deceased","1300–1377":"1300–1377","1330–1389":"1330–1389","1331–Male":"1331–Deceased","1335–Female":"1335–Deceased","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1275–1300":"1275–1300","1330":"1330","1275":"1275","1382":"1382","1270":"1270","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1389":"1389","1377":"1377","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1331":"1331","about 1331":"about 1331","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Ellesmere, Shropshire, England":"Ellesmere, Shropshire, England","Ellesmere, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ellesmere, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Ellesmere Port, Cheshire, England":"Netherpool, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"verch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Orlo.","German: variant of   Ferch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferch","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]},{"name":"Jenkin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal names <i>Jankin</i>, <i>Jenkin</i>, and <i>Jonkin</i>, pet forms of <i>Jan</i>, <i>Jen</i>, and <i>Jon</i> + the hypocoristic suffix <i>-kin</i>. In Middle English, names in <i>-kin</i> were often used to name the younger of two family members with the same personal name."],"variants":[{"name":"Jenkins","meanings":["English and Welsh: variant of   Jenkin  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. <i>Jenkins</i> is one of the most common surnames in England, especially southwestern England, but is also especially associated with Wales."]},{"name":"Jenks","meanings":["English (West Midlands): from the Middle English personal name <i>Jenke</i> (a shortening of the personal name <i>Jenkin</i>, <i>Jankin</i>; see   Jenkin  ), with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","History: Joseph Jenks (1602–83), the descendant of an old Welsh family, was born in England and traveled to Saugus, near Lynn, MA, in 1642 to assist in the development of America's first iron works. His son, Joseph Jenckes (sic), followed in 1650, founded Pawtucket, RI, and raised four sons who held places of respect and distinction in RI, including one who served as governor for five years."]},{"name":"Jenkinson","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): from the Middle English personal names <i>Jankin</i>, <i>Jenkin</i>, or <i>Jonkin</i> (see   Jenkin  ) + <i>son</i>."]}]},{"name":"Silotta","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Amedeo, Amedio, Angelo, Carmine, Domenic, Donato, Francesco, Giuseppe, Luigi, Palma, Pasquale, Santo.","Italian (southern):","from a French personal name, <i>Bil(l)ot</i>, a short form of <i>Robillot</i>, a pet form of   Robert  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bilotti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Americo, Carlo, Mario, Antonio, Armando, Dino, Gaetano, Orlando, Roberto, Sabino, Sal, Salvatore, Vincenzo.","Italian: variant of   Bilotta  ."]},{"name":"Robert","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":5,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":18,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":72,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Silotta verch Jenkin was born in 1310, in Ellesmere, Shropshire, England, her father, Jenkin Frankton Lord of Welsh West Frankton, was 40 and her mother, Jane Touchet, was 35. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Madoc Kynaston."},"et":{"1310–":"1310–Surnud","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1300–1377":"1300–1377","1330–1389":"1330–1389"